## Q1

### (a)

#### Version 1
```{r}
#' Title: the v1 function for dice game
#'
#' @param n - the number of dice to roll
#'
#' @return total winnings or loses
#' @export
#'
#' @examples
play_dice_v1 <- function(n){
  c <- -2*n
  # roll dice for n times
  for (i in 1:n){
    # randomly pick a dice from 1~6
    dice <- sample(1:6, 1, replace = TRUE)
    # if dice == 2 or 4 or 6, add corresponding scores
    if (dice == 2 | dice == 4 | dice == 6){
      # c - current cost
      c <- c + dice
    }
  }
  return(c)
}

# example for 10 dice
play_dice_v1(10)
```

#### Version 2

```{r}
#' Title: the v2 function for dice game
#'
#' @param n - the number of dice to roll
#'
#' @return total winnings or loses
#' @export
#'
#' @examples
play_dice_v2 <- function(n){
  # randomly pick a dice from 1~6
  dice <- sample(1:6, n, replace = TRUE)
  # if dice == 2 or 4 or 6, add corresponding scores
  dice <- ifelse(dice %% 2 == 0, dice, 0)
  c <- -2*n + sum(dice)
  return(c)
}

# example for 5 dice
play_dice_v2(5)
```

#### Version 3
```{r}
#' Title: the v3 function for dice game
#'
#' @param n - the number of dice to roll
#'
#' @return total winnings or loses
#' @export
#'
#' @examples
play_dice_v3 <- function(n){
  dice <- sample(1:6, n, replace = TRUE)
  table <- table(dice)
  name <- names(table)
  table <- ifelse(as.numeric(name) %% 2 == 0, table*as.numeric(name), 0)
  c <- -2*n + sum(table)
  return(c)
}

# example for 5 dice
play_dice_v3(5)
```

#### Version 4

```{r}
#' Title: the v4 function for dice game
#'
#' @param n - the number of dice to roll
#'
#' @return total winnings or loses
#' @export
#'
#' @examples
play_dice_v4 <- function(n){
  dice <- sample(1:6, n, replace = TRUE)
  dice_v4 <- sapply(dice, set_value <- function(dice){
    ifelse(dice %% 2 == 0, dice, 0)
  })
  c <- -2*n + sum(dice_v4)
  return(c)
}

# example for 10 dice
play_dice_v4(10)
```

### (d)

```{r}
# the speed of low input
microbenchmark(play_dice_v1(100), play_dice_v2(100), play_dice_v3(100), play_dice_v4(100))

# the speed of large input
microbenchmark(play_dice_v1(10000), play_dice_v2(10000), play_dice_v3(10000), play_dice_v4(10000))
```

#### Discussion
The vectorization is fastest, and `table()` is the second fastest, while `for` loop and `apply` are slow but `for` loop is much slower. The reason vectorization is fastest has to do with the fact that the built-in R function `sum()` is implemented in the compiled language, which is fast. As for `table()`, although it is efficient a lot, create the table still give computational costs. For `for` loop, R needs to interpret the meaning of code and also `for` loop requires indexing into the value using the subset function in each iteration, which is time-consuming. The `sapply` function improves efficiency compared to `for` loops but it still cost time in some matrix computations.

The speed difference between v1 & v4 and v2 & v3 is more significant when we input a large number, but the speed difference between v2 & v3 is less significant when we input a large number.

### (e)

Assume that the standard of a game is a fair or not is its mean = 0.
Suppose $H_0: mean = 0, H_1: mean \ne 0$.
```{r}
set.seed(1024)
mcrep <- 10000                  # The number of replications
n <- c(5, 10, 100)                         # Roll size we are studying
# Create an empty matrix for saving result of each roll.
sim <- array(NA, dim = c(mcrep, 1))        
for (j in 1:3){
  n0 <- n[j]
  for (i in 1:mcrep){
    sim[i] <- play_dice_v1(n0)
  }
  # calculate and print the p-value of data
  print(paste("The p-value for roll size =", n0, "is", t.test(sim)$p.value))
}
```
Since p-value is large, we can accept $H_0$. This game is fair.

### (e)
Follow by the formula:

$$\hat{\beta} = (X^TX)^{-1}X^Ty$$
```{r}
# Set up X and y
ff <- Highway_mpg ~ Horsepower*Torque + Height + Length + Width + factor(Released_Year)
X <- model.matrix(ff, df_gas)
y <- df_gas$Highway_mpg
# calculate X^TX
XtX <- t(X) %*% X
# inverse of X^TX
XtXi <- solve(XtX)
# Generate \hat{beta}
beta <- XtXi %*% t(X) %*% y
beta
```

```{r}
# Test if I get the same result as `lm()` did prior (the error is within 10^{-10}).
if (all(coef(model_d)-beta[,1] < 10^{-10})){
  print("You get the same result!")
}else{
  print("Sorry...They are different, please try again :(")
}
```
